There are several types of learning, categorized based on theories, approaches, and settings. Here’s an overview

Visual learners understand best through pictures, charts, and diagrams. They prefer shapes and patterns over words or speech. Teachers can help by using tools like graphic organizers to explain ideas clearly.

Auditory learners learn best by hearing and speaking. They enjoy lectures, group discussions, and talking through ideas. They often figure things out by speaking first, rather than planning what to say.

Reading & writing learners understand best through words. They enjoy reading and do well with written tasks like stories or reports. They prefer learning through text, such as reading books or writing notes. Teachers can help by asking them to explain diagrams or charts in writing, which they can review later to remember the information.

Kinesthetic learners learn best by doing. They like hands-on activities, real-life examples, and practicing skills through physical actions. Teachers can help by giving them practical tasks, like recreating experiments or working through examples to understand new ideas.
Now let’s determine your learning style through a quick evaluation.

Select Internal Contact from the Channel/Direction drop down
Select Billing Enquiry from the Type of Contact drop down. The status should remain Open.
The Categorisation needs to be the same as what is advised on Agent Assist for the commitment type you are raising. In this example we are choosing Move In.
Choose Process Move In
Choose Move in completed DD set up
Click on the calendar icon next to received date
This need to be the date you are raising the commitment. In this case the 9th July.
If the Responsible group field has not auto populated click on the two boxes.
Type in the code csc_tsp in the Search term field.
Click Search
Double click on the relevant line.
Click into two squares on Interaction Centre Agent field
Add your last name (agent) into the Last name field - in this case 'Hall'
Add your first name (agent) into the First name field - in this case 'Dawn'
Click Search and double click on your own CPT - in this case CPT-HAD
Under Notes in the box that say’s ‘write note…’ please add a brief note of the conversation and what you have advised the customer.

Leave the Employee Responsible field blank and click on the 2 boxes at the side of Responsible group

For this example, choose DWP instruction.
Click the clock / calendar icon at the side of Commitment Date
Select the correct amount of days / hours the commitment needs to be worked by – in this case 2 working days.

In the 'Write note...' section add the instructions you want carrying out in the commitment. When putting notes on the internal commitment. Please use the commitment matrix for the notes. This helps to give clear request on what action needs to be updated.
It’s closing time for this module.
So, let’s recap all your learnings, move it to the phones.
I hope you have learned something new.
Throughout the call, you work hard to gain trust, establish credibility, discover needs, and utilize that information to find the right product for that caller’s needs.
However, you can’t get the sale if you don’t ask! That’s the importance of closing.
We should be asking for the sale immediately after providing the price.
This is why a best practice during the discover process is to ask the budget question last, because it is a natural transition to price.
By asking the budget question last, you are in a better position to successfully close because you have all your information you need to know to offer the right product based on the customers needs.
There are multiple closing techniques you can use.
Find the one that works best for your personality and call style.
You don’t have to use the same one every time, don’t be afraid to step outside your comfort zone and try something new!
Hearing no can and will happen to everyone in a sales role.
There is not a closing technique that guarantees everyone will say yes.
Remember to catch it, catch it, change it when it comes to hearing no on calls.
You will hear more no’s than yes’s and that’s okay.
So don’t be afraid to go for no - that means you at least asked for the sale!
It’s officially closing time, open all the queues and let you out into those calls!

Since you are taking this sym, you have obviously learned how to launch a sym – way to go!

The first is click the play icon next to any of the syms shown on your Home page.
The second is from your My Exercises tab, let’s head there now.
Here is where you will find all syms that have been assigned to you as well as your progress.
As you continue your journey in the DSC, you may have more than 10 rows of assignments and will need to expand your rows per page or view the other pages to find assignments.
If you see a stacked icon, that indicates that is a sym module, which means it contains more than one sym. Click the icon to expand and see the included syms.
On the right, you can see what syms you have already completed in that module.
To launch a sym from your exercises, you can click on the play icon on the left of the sym or module.

As you already saw, you can select if you would like to proceed with completing a Practice or Test version of the sym.
You can also select a different sym to launch from the module list by clicking the play icon on the sym tile.
Some syms, like the one you are taking right now, require verbal responses. It is important to make sure the correct microphone setting is selected so SymTrain can hear you and record your response.
Before starting your first sym of the day, you should check your hardware.

Using your company provided headset is the best practice to ensure that SymTrain can pick up your voice clearly. To use the headset while in a sym, make sure it is plugged into your laptop and not your phone.
While you can select your laptop’s built in microphone as an option, depending on your desk setup that microphone might be too far away to pick up your voice clearly.
Let’s practice what this would look like.
For the purposes of this sym, we will give you a prompt to speak into the microphone.
When you a ready, click Start Recording for a prompt to appear at the bottom of the screen.
Say the prompt out loud, then click the Next icon that appears to continue.
Mic check. Test one, two, three.
Great job! After recording, there will be a playback button that will allow you to hear how you sound to ensure quality recording throughout any sym that day.
That was just a simulated practice. Be sure to check this feature out for real before your next sym.
The final area to explore is the Playback. We will review that next sym.

Fantastic job completing your first sym! Let’s stay on track and head over to the next one where we learn how to view your sym playback.
Welcome back! Congratulations on completing your first sym a moment ago. Now let’s see how you did.
Before we get started, I want to draw your attention to the sym time length on the opening screen of each sym.
This lets you know on average how long it should take to complete the sym.
Take a moment to look for the “Time Elapsed” located at the top of this sym.
As you work through syms, be sure to keep an eye on your pace so you can finish within the allotted time for the assignment.
Let’s proceed full steam ahead!
Reminder, here are some best practices for navigating throughout a sym. Click the arrow when you are ready to continue.
After completing a sym, you will be directed to a screen that looks like this.
From here you can already see your Completion Time, Keyword Score, and Click Score.
To view more details on your sym score, click View Playback.
This playback view provides more insight on your performance.
You can see if you completed the sym in Practice or Test Mode, the day and time completed, and you can even click re-attempt and do it again from here.
Here is that completion time again.

Completion time is important because if it is taking you longer to navigate the conversation and screens, it can be an indication that you just need to practice the sym more to learn the process better.
Let’s break down the other stats on the screen, starting with Keyword Score.
Keywords are structure words in the conversation that are good word choices or can even be compliance words that must be said. If the sym has no agent lines, you will not have a keyword score.
The DSC is not a scripted environment. The key words chosen throughout the syms will be ones that everyone should say.
For example, everyone should state “Mutual of Omaha” in your call introduction.
The first number is your keyword score, and the second is the possible score.
In that last sym, I got 3 out of 4 keywords correct.
To see which one I missed, I can scroll down to find it in the playback.
Words highlighted green indicate you got the keyword correct, while red indicates it was missed.
Here I can see that I missed the first word, hello.
You can click the Trainee Response to jump to that part of the recording, then click Play to listen.
After listening to my playback, I could here that I said hello, but the microphone didn’t start picking up right away so the greeting was cut off.
Technology is not perfect. There could also be times where it thought you said a different word. For example, application and occupation can sound similar to a computer.
That is why the training team and your supervisors review playback on lower scoring syms.
This allows them to see if it was a system error or a coaching opportunity.
Scroll back to the top to look at the rest of the sym score.
Let’s review Click Score next.
Click Score is scoring where on the visual components of the sym you navigated and clicked through during the process. Click score will only be in visual syms.
The first number is your click score, and the second is the possible score.
In that last sym, I got 19 out of 19 clicks correct. Way to go me! That is a good indicator that I understand the process in the sym.
Confidence, Concentration and Energy are your sentiment scores.
These scores are calculated by the level of intent you deliver the script line in the areas of confidence, concentration and energy.
These are not calculated on your voice or tone, but on how confident your level of intent is, your focus or concentration level, and your pace or energy level.
The sentiment score is calculated for the entire sym, not one part or another.
My Energy score was Medium. I can click Insights to view more.
This is where I can find insight on how to improve that score if I were to take it again, or helpful advice for future syms.
Next let’s look at the Sym Accuracy Score.
This measures how well your response matched the intent of what the customer was asking in the customer script line.
SymTrain is still working on improvements to the Sym Accuracy score, and this is being monitored by the training team at the moment.
The final stat to look at is the Sym Score.
This will equal a combined score of the different scoring options for that sym. If this is a beginner sym your score should be in the 80% range.
Again, technology is not perfect. That is why the training team and supervisors will take a look at those lower scores to see if it was a system error or a coaching opportunity for improvement.
Now that we’ve reviewed how to look at detailed playback after completing a sym, let’s head to the Playback page.
The Playback page provides an overview of your sym performance for all your completed syms.
To view the detailed playback for any sym, simply click the Actions icon.

In this sym, we will review how the UCSL application varies based on state.
Reminder that we can not C O P whole life applications for Connecticut or Montana.
New York has its own application for our Guaranteed Whole Life policy. We’ll go into detail on New York later.
The states in red on the map have some different verbatim messages that will appear in the e App.
Remember that these boxes are verbatim statements.
You should not try to memorize these, as they may change for each state.
Always be sure to read what's on your screen word for word.
One such example is with California, the final application verbatim has an additional paragraph regarding fraud.
This allows us to be compliant with California law. The fraud statement is also provided in the policy documents.
Again, this is why you should not memorize verbatims. Simply follow the application.
Another California law requires we obtain an email address from our California elders (which is age 65 or older) so we can send them pertinent disclosures before the application is completed.
To comply with the California law, there is a verbatim early in the application regarding consent to electronic delivery and e-signature.
The verbatim and email address field is mandatory, and the e-app will prevent you from continuing the application if you do not enter in a valid customer email address.
Once you have entered the email address in the box you must press the Send button. If you don’t press this button, the e-app will prevent you from continuing the application.
If the email fails to send, the Send button will turn red and will say Fail.
The e-app will prevent you from moving forward until an email has successfully been sent.
If the email successfully sends, the Send button will turn green and will say Sent.
Once you have received the green Sent message, you need to ask the customer to verbally confirm they received the email.
This is what the email that the customer receives looks like.
Here’s another question that will only appear during the application in certain states.
These states have state special questions and verbiage that is required to be read about accessing PDF files via the internet and providing their consent to receive electronic documents.
The state requires we review this electronic consent.
We're asking if they can access the internet in any shape or form.
If they say no, you can clarify by asking if they have access to the internet (smart phone, library, etc.).

If they still answer No, you will need to explain to the applicant that if they are not able to access the internet, or do not provide their consent, you will not be able to take their application over the phone and it will need to be mailed to them. This may delay the processing time and the effective date of their policy.
Let’s practice a state specific scenario! Click the arrow when you are ready to begin.
Have you received an application packet?
No.
Are you able to open, view and save P D F files via the internet?
No.
Do you have access to the internet by using a smart phone or going to the library?
Oh, yes. I can do that.

I am required to obtain your consent for the delivery of electronic documents to you whether through the internet, email, web, text, instant message, digital media or the like. Your consent applies to all documents Mutual of Omaha may be required to deliver to you in writing. Any document provided to you electronically may be provided in paper upon your request. You may withdraw your consent at any time. If you withdraw your consent, I will not be able to complete your application over the phone and I will need to mail you a paper application. You may withdraw your consent, update your contact information or obtain a paper copy of any document for no charge, by contacting (800) 775-6000. You will need access to a computer or other device which provides internet access or email, as well as the ability to open, view and save a PDF, text or html file.
Do I have your consent to provide you with the necessary documents electronically?
Yes
Disclosures are made available to you at the following website: http://www.mutualofomaha.com/wholelifedocuments
